WEBVTT

00:00.454 --> 00:03.940
I want the world see what it would miss
if <i>Bombshell</i> will run away.

00:03.982 --> 00:06.501
♪ The line

00:06.566 --> 00:08.716
Previously on <i>Smash...</i>

00:08.718 --> 00:09.767
Oh, my God.

00:09.769 --> 00:11.402
You're letting me go
because of her.

00:11.404 --> 00:12.653
Word on the street is

00:12.655 --> 00:14.188
that you couldn't
hack it on <i>Bombshell.</i>

00:14.190 --> 00:16.107
We're now allowed
to resume work on the show.

00:16.109 --> 00:18.225
How much do you need?

00:18.227 --> 00:20.361
♪ Mama makes three

00:20.363 --> 00:22.697
beyond directing
one of Broadway's biggest stars

00:22.699 --> 00:24.415
in <i>The Wiz,</i>
yes, I have several offers.

00:24.417 --> 00:25.583
They're letting you go.

00:25.585 --> 00:28.319
Just because I shagged
a couple of actresses?

00:28.321 --> 00:30.288
♪ I'm falling, baby

00:30.290 --> 00:32.540
♪ through the sky,
through the sky ♪

00:32.542 --> 00:34.292
Your friend said you guys
are writing a musical.

00:34.294 --> 00:35.576
I mean, I'd love to hear more.

00:35.578 --> 00:37.712
♪ I'm ready to drown

00:37.714 --> 00:39.063
Stay out of this, princess.

00:39.065 --> 00:41.115
I just think you're
really talented... I want to help.

00:41.117 --> 00:43.751
Would it have killed you
to do something for me for once?

00:43.753 --> 00:45.887
This is everything
I've written so far.

00:45.889 --> 00:47.121
♪ Just walk away

00:47.123 --> 00:49.456
You are a singular talent.
Don't give up.

00:49.458 --> 00:51.676
Is this a bad time? Do you
have company or something?

00:51.678 --> 00:53.261
Oh, hi.

00:53.263 --> 00:56.347
- What did Ivy want?
- Nothing important.

01:00.202 --> 01:03.187
<i>[Good for you</i> playing]

01:03.189 --> 01:11.189
♪

01:12.865 --> 01:16.083
♪ if you start the party

01:16.085 --> 01:19.370
♪ don't end up leaving early

01:19.372 --> 01:24.592
♪ 'cause I've been waiting
for you all night long ♪

01:24.594 --> 01:27.795
♪ if you're falling

01:27.797 --> 01:31.048
♪ I'll make it easy
for you ♪

01:31.050 --> 01:36.771
♪ 'cause I've been waiting
for them all night long ♪

01:36.773 --> 01:39.673
♪ you've got me dizzy

01:39.675 --> 01:43.227
♪ it's quite a show

01:43.229 --> 01:45.813
♪ with all this spinning

01:45.815 --> 01:49.016
♪ I won't let me
let you go ♪

01:49.018 --> 01:52.119
♪ oh, I

01:52.121 --> 01:57.625
♪ oh, I think
I could be good for you ♪

01:57.627 --> 02:02.580
♪ oh, I could be good
for you ♪

02:02.582 --> 02:06.884
It's a good song.
So what?

02:06.886 --> 02:09.870
All their songs are good.

02:09.872 --> 02:13.224
If they had an album,
I'd buy it, maybe.

02:13.226 --> 02:15.509
But I'm a director
of musicals,

02:15.511 --> 02:16.978
and there's
no musical here.

02:16.980 --> 02:19.046
Well, that's because
I'm only playing you the songs.

02:19.048 --> 02:20.714
Which you did
last week as well.

02:20.716 --> 02:22.516
And you liked them. I thought
you'd want to hear more.

02:22.518 --> 02:25.386
With you conveniently singing
the demo this time?

02:25.388 --> 02:27.488
Well, it is a song
my character would sing.

02:27.490 --> 02:28.639
She's an aspiring pop star.

02:28.641 --> 02:29.857
Oh, there are characters,
are there?

02:29.859 --> 02:31.058
Is there a plot as well?

02:31.060 --> 02:32.393
Of course,
and the writers would love

02:32.395 --> 02:33.861
to tell you
about it themselves.

02:33.863 --> 02:36.730
Can't I just read the book?

02:36.732 --> 02:37.999
They're still working on it.

02:38.001 --> 02:39.917
Meet with them. Let them explain
their vision to you.

02:39.919 --> 02:41.752
Look...

02:41.754 --> 02:43.254
I think it's great
that you're hustling

02:43.256 --> 02:44.738
while <i>Bombshell</i>
<i>sorts itself out,</i>

02:44.740 --> 02:47.208
but new musicals
take years to develop.

02:47.210 --> 02:49.927
I need something right now...
Something big.

02:49.929 --> 02:52.513
This is big.
I promise.

02:52.515 --> 02:53.747
How about later today?

02:53.749 --> 02:55.416
No, I've got a meeting.

02:55.418 --> 02:58.519
The producers of <i>The Wiz</i>
can't find my replacement yet.

02:58.521 --> 02:59.971
Surprise, surprise.

02:59.973 --> 03:02.123
I've convinced Ronnie
to hear me out.

03:02.125 --> 03:05.693
It's been a while since
I've had something to prove.

03:05.695 --> 03:07.194
It's quite refreshing.

03:07.196 --> 03:10.982
Then you know
how these guys feel.

03:10.984 --> 03:13.117
All right,
I will meet them.

03:13.119 --> 03:16.954
Yay!
Yes! Yes!

03:16.956 --> 03:19.991
So tomorrow then?

03:19.993 --> 03:21.876
So what's going on, Eileen?
Do we have news?

03:21.878 --> 03:23.160
Well, we all agree

03:23.162 --> 03:26.130
there are some problems
on the show that need fixing,

03:26.132 --> 03:29.083
so let's hone in on yours...
The book.

03:29.085 --> 03:30.568
Of course.

03:30.570 --> 03:33.154
Tom and I have already
started compiling some notes,

03:33.156 --> 03:35.172
talking
about a few new numbers,

03:35.174 --> 03:37.642
maybe reordering
some of the scenes.

03:37.644 --> 03:39.293
I fear that's not going
to be enough.

03:39.295 --> 03:41.679
I think we need
a fresh eye on the show.

03:41.681 --> 03:43.764
- A fresh eye?
- Yes.

03:43.766 --> 03:45.850
There's someone
I want you to meet.

03:45.852 --> 03:47.601
His name is Peter gilman,

03:47.603 --> 03:50.004
and I think
you'll like him very much.

03:50.006 --> 03:52.907
And what does
this Peter gilman do?

03:52.909 --> 03:55.026
He's
a professional dramaturg.

03:55.028 --> 03:57.528
A dramaturg?
Are... are you joking?

03:57.530 --> 04:00.698
[Laughing]
Of course she's joking.

04:00.700 --> 04:03.334
Well, actually, it's a very
common practice these days.

04:03.336 --> 04:06.487
Most of the big shows use one
to reshape the book.

04:06.489 --> 04:09.290
Look, I know
I dropped the ball in Boston.

04:09.292 --> 04:11.542
But Tom and I
are incredibly focused,

04:11.544 --> 04:13.344
ready to work 24/7.

04:13.346 --> 04:17.098
And since neither of us
has, actually, a life anymore...

04:17.100 --> 04:18.548
I'm sorry.
There just isn't enough time.

04:18.551 --> 04:20.351
We've been allowed back
into rehearsal,

04:20.353 --> 04:23.003
but the most we can do
is restage a few numbers

04:23.005 --> 04:24.555
if we don't have a new book.

04:24.557 --> 04:26.691
And we need it fast.

04:26.693 --> 04:30.911
I'll set the meeting
for 3:00 P.M. today.

04:30.913 --> 04:34.865
[Ivy vocalizing]

04:34.867 --> 04:38.402
That was really good, Ivy.
We'll be in touch.

04:41.373 --> 04:43.857
Thank you.

04:43.859 --> 04:46.544
Bernie...

04:46.546 --> 04:48.329
I know I shouldn't be
asking this,

04:48.331 --> 04:51.415
but I was wondering
if I could come back

04:51.417 --> 04:53.384
and read for the role
of cecile as well.

04:53.386 --> 04:54.585
- Cecile?
- Mm-hmm.

04:54.587 --> 04:57.054
Every actress in town
wants to do that part.

04:57.056 --> 04:59.873
Well, I understand,
but I read the script,

04:59.875 --> 05:04.178
and I really think I could bring
something special to it.

05:04.180 --> 05:05.679
Aren't you committed
to <i>Bombshell</i>

05:05.681 --> 05:08.065
when it moves to Broadway?

05:14.156 --> 05:15.722
Okay. Okay.

05:15.724 --> 05:18.492
I'm going to give you a shot,
but don't let me down.

05:18.494 --> 05:19.910
I won't.

05:19.912 --> 05:22.246
Thanks, Bernie.

05:22.248 --> 05:23.864
♪ Here I am, alone

05:23.866 --> 05:26.117
♪ though it feels the same

05:26.119 --> 05:32.123
♪ I don't know
where I'm going ♪

05:32.125 --> 05:33.791
♪ I'm here on my own

05:33.793 --> 05:37.344
♪ and it's not a game

05:37.346 --> 05:42.266
♪ and a strange wind
is blowing ♪

05:42.268 --> 05:44.552
♪ I am so amazed

05:44.554 --> 05:47.605
♪ by the things
that I see here ♪

05:47.607 --> 05:49.590
♪ don't want to be afraid

05:49.592 --> 05:52.643
♪ I just don't want
to be here ♪

05:52.645 --> 05:57.898
♪ in my mind,
this is clear ♪

05:57.900 --> 06:03.437
♪ what am I doing here?

06:03.439 --> 06:06.290
♪ I wish I was

06:06.292 --> 06:14.292
♪ home

06:17.886 --> 06:20.004
- [clapping]
- [Chuckles]

06:20.006 --> 06:21.589
<i>The Wiz</i>
has never sounded better.

06:21.591 --> 06:25.426
Just familiarizing myself
with the music.

06:25.428 --> 06:27.678
[Sighs]

06:27.680 --> 06:30.481
Which one you like?

06:30.483 --> 06:31.665
None of them.

06:31.667 --> 06:33.350
Really?
Why?

06:33.352 --> 06:34.351
Well, does the innocence
of Dorothy

06:34.353 --> 06:35.536
have to be
quite so on the nose?

06:35.538 --> 06:37.021
And why is it period?

06:37.023 --> 06:40.191
It should feel now,
not nostalgic.

06:40.193 --> 06:41.692
That's why we haven't found
a director.

06:41.694 --> 06:43.027
The producers
keep sending me people

06:43.029 --> 06:44.311
with the same safe take.

06:44.313 --> 06:47.081
I want to do something exciting,
for a change.

06:47.083 --> 06:48.949
Yeah, well, producers
rarely have vision.

06:48.951 --> 06:50.918
That's why they need us
to show it to them.

06:50.920 --> 06:52.703
Look...

06:52.705 --> 06:54.588
I know I'm not
their favorite person right now,

06:54.590 --> 06:56.257
but what if I could change
their mind,

06:56.259 --> 06:58.926
show them how family-friendly
I can be?

06:58.928 --> 07:00.961
I don't think
that's possible.

07:00.963 --> 07:02.880
Oh, I do.

07:02.882 --> 07:06.433
We could stage a scene together,
just you and me.

07:06.435 --> 07:09.687
How about
<i>as soon as I get home?</i>

07:09.689 --> 07:12.389
Derek Wills...
Auditioning?

07:12.391 --> 07:14.341
Well, let's just call it
rubbing their noses in it,

07:14.343 --> 07:17.144
but if it gets it back
for me, then, yes...

07:17.146 --> 07:18.379
It's an audition.

07:18.381 --> 07:21.782
All right, let me see
if I can set it up.

07:23.518 --> 07:25.352
You know what happens.

07:25.354 --> 07:27.354
People hear
that you have a dramaturg,

07:27.356 --> 07:31.008
and the rumor gets out
that the show's in trouble.

07:31.010 --> 07:32.393
Okay, right.

07:32.395 --> 07:36.797
But what about the part
where people think I've lost it,

07:36.799 --> 07:38.148
that I couldn't do it
on my own?

07:38.150 --> 07:40.351
Some dramaturgs
really do help.

07:40.353 --> 07:42.302
Hi.
Three for levitt, please.

07:42.304 --> 07:45.973
Yeah. And then there are some
who say they're going to help

07:45.975 --> 07:48.242
but then end up suing
for credit.

07:48.244 --> 07:51.278
Enjoy your meal.

07:52.414 --> 07:54.615
I looked the guy up
on I.B.D.B.

07:54.617 --> 07:58.002
He's had one legitimate
production in New York,

07:58.004 --> 07:59.453
and it was a play.

07:59.455 --> 08:00.504
Eileen said he shepherded

08:00.506 --> 08:02.322
three musicals
currently on Broadway,

08:02.324 --> 08:03.674
and they're all hits.

08:03.676 --> 08:05.676
And he didn't take credit
on any of them.

08:05.678 --> 08:07.094
A man who makes his living

08:07.096 --> 08:09.597
feeding off the work
of other writers

08:09.599 --> 08:12.750
without creating anything
of his own is not a Shepherd.

08:12.752 --> 08:14.134
He's a parasite.

08:14.136 --> 08:17.204
Hi. I'm Peter,
the parasite.

08:17.206 --> 08:18.722
Nice to meet you both.

08:18.724 --> 08:22.309
Uh, don't worry.

08:22.311 --> 08:23.811
This part
is always awkward.

08:23.813 --> 08:25.212
Dramaturgs are
like dentists.

08:25.214 --> 08:26.680
No one ever wants
to see them,

08:26.682 --> 08:29.266
but once the pain wears off,
you're always glad you went.

08:29.268 --> 08:30.734
- I have perfect teeth.
- It's true.

08:30.736 --> 08:32.937
She's never had a cavity.
Not in my whole life, nope.

08:32.938 --> 08:34.989
Look, I know you guys
don't want me here.

08:34.991 --> 08:36.722
But you should know, I wouldn't
even take this meeting

08:36.725 --> 08:38.075
if I did not love your work.

08:38.077 --> 08:40.110
Really?
What have you seen?

08:40.111 --> 08:41.779
<i>Three on a match,</i>
of course,

08:41.780 --> 08:43.563
<i>Temps,</i> which I thought
was brilliant...

08:43.566 --> 08:45.583
Didn't get a fair shake
from the <i>Times...</i>

08:45.585 --> 08:46.667
Uh, <i>Heaven on Earth,</i>

08:46.669 --> 08:47.918
a really fun night
at the theater.

08:47.920 --> 08:50.499
And I've been to three
Houston/Levitt nights at Joe's pub.

08:50.525 --> 08:51.505
There were only two.

08:51.507 --> 08:53.090
Well, I loved the 7:30
so much last time,

08:53.092 --> 08:56.176
I stayed for the 10:00.
- [Chuckles]

08:56.178 --> 08:58.596
<i>Bombshell</i> is your baby.
I get that.

08:58.598 --> 09:00.714
If you were to work with me,
I would only be the midwife

09:00.716 --> 09:02.349
helping to Usher it safely
into the world.

09:02.351 --> 09:03.684
You read it,
I assume?

09:03.686 --> 09:06.287
Oh, two or three times,
just to get a sense, yeah.

09:06.289 --> 09:08.722
I mean, I have some thoughts,
but there's a great foundation.

09:08.724 --> 09:10.140
I think
it'll be extraordinary.

09:10.142 --> 09:13.727
I've got a, uh, list of writers
that I've worked with

09:13.729 --> 09:16.113
who will apparently
sing my praises.

09:16.115 --> 09:17.564
[Cell phone vibrates]

09:17.566 --> 09:20.901
Ah, I am so sorry.
Would you excuse me a minute?

09:24.122 --> 09:26.957
[Scoffs] We know half
of the people on this list,

09:26.959 --> 09:29.793
and we didn't know
he worked on their shows.

09:29.795 --> 09:32.779
He did that one?

09:32.781 --> 09:35.633
I don't know.
He seems pretty credible.

09:35.635 --> 09:39.303
[Sighs, scoffs]

09:39.305 --> 09:42.806
God, I hope
we don't regret this.

09:42.808 --> 09:44.808
- He wants to meet? No joke?
- He loves the songs.

09:44.810 --> 09:46.343
Now he just has
to hear the story.

09:46.345 --> 09:47.478
Oh, my God.

09:47.480 --> 09:49.713
Derek Wills directing our show...
I would die.

09:49.715 --> 09:51.598
Whoa, slow down there, Kyle.

09:51.600 --> 09:53.350
It's just a meeting.

09:53.352 --> 09:55.769
The guy's probably just being
polite to his star, anyway.

09:55.771 --> 09:57.488
Derek's never polite.

09:57.490 --> 09:59.306
He wants to meet
tomorrow night at 9:00.

09:59.308 --> 10:01.825
Tomorrow?

10:01.827 --> 10:03.327
I know you know
the story, Kyle.

10:03.329 --> 10:04.578
You've told it to me.

10:04.580 --> 10:06.280
Of course I do.

10:06.282 --> 10:07.831
I'm just a little nervous.

10:07.833 --> 10:09.033
Well, try not to be.

10:09.035 --> 10:10.834
You only get one shot
with a guy like Derek.

10:10.836 --> 10:12.419
What did you have to do
to get yours?

10:12.421 --> 10:15.422
It's what she didn't do.

10:15.424 --> 10:17.591
Oh, wait.
That was a private story?

10:17.593 --> 10:19.293
Hey, don't worry
about us.

10:19.295 --> 10:22.463
One shot's all we need.

10:22.465 --> 10:23.465
Hit it.

10:23.466 --> 10:27.017
[Up-tempo jazz music]

10:27.019 --> 10:29.019
One, two, three, four,
five, six, seven, eight.

10:29.021 --> 10:30.554
One, two, three, four,
five, six, seven, eight.

10:30.556 --> 10:32.839
One, two, three, four, five,
six, seven, eight.

10:32.841 --> 10:34.224
One, two, three, four,
five, six...

10:34.226 --> 10:36.110
One, two, ree, four, five,
six, seven, eight.

10:36.112 --> 10:37.911
One, two, three, four,
five, six...

10:37.913 --> 10:39.329
One, two, three, four, five,
six, seven, eight.

10:39.331 --> 10:42.149
Five, six, seven, eight!

10:47.211 --> 10:48.795
Wow.

10:48.797 --> 10:52.549
You didn't get all of this
from, uh, your one play.

10:52.551 --> 10:54.100
[Chuckles]

10:54.102 --> 10:56.853
Script doctoring
must pay well.

10:56.855 --> 11:01.074
Well, my collaborators
make more.

11:01.076 --> 11:04.227
There's, uh, something
you should know about me, Julia,

11:04.229 --> 11:08.064
is I'm a bit of a snob
when it comes to my coffee.

11:08.066 --> 11:09.733
I prepare each cup
individually,

11:09.735 --> 11:12.402
with this pour-over carafe.

11:12.404 --> 11:13.737
You smell that?

11:13.739 --> 11:15.622
Mmm.
Isn't it incredible?

11:15.624 --> 11:17.957
I get the beans flown in
directly from this little shop...

11:17.959 --> 11:20.210
I don't like coffee.
I never did.

11:20.212 --> 11:21.711
I drink tea.

11:21.713 --> 11:25.081
Why don't you just give me
your thoughts,

11:25.083 --> 11:26.750
since you seem to have...

11:26.752 --> 11:28.551
[Chuckles]
A lot of them.

11:28.553 --> 11:31.454
[Chuckles] Well,
I wouldn't say I have a lot...

11:31.456 --> 11:33.056
Yet.

11:33.058 --> 11:36.926
Uh, I can start
with some big-picture stuff.

11:36.928 --> 11:39.195
Now, I apologize if this
sounds a little reductive,

11:39.197 --> 11:43.483
but <i>bombshel</i> as it stands now,
it's not a Broadway musical.

11:43.485 --> 11:45.769
Excuse me?

11:45.771 --> 11:47.670
[Scoffs]
It's a biopic...

11:47.672 --> 11:49.656
And not a very
in-depth one, at that.

11:49.658 --> 11:51.191
I mean, there's no character
development

11:51.193 --> 11:52.242
outside of the songs,

11:52.244 --> 11:53.910
which are, admittedly,
the best part...

11:53.912 --> 11:56.413
Did you just call
my book shallow?

11:56.415 --> 11:59.282
Well, no.
No, not at all.

11:59.284 --> 12:01.785
Two-dimensional maybe.

12:01.787 --> 12:03.169
[Laughs]

12:03.171 --> 12:05.922
The audience cried
when Marilyn died.

12:05.924 --> 12:09.342
We had standing ovations
every night.

12:09.344 --> 12:13.096
It was Boston.

12:13.098 --> 12:14.831
I think
you would feel differently

12:14.833 --> 12:16.399
if you had seen it.

12:16.401 --> 12:17.600
I shouldn't have to.

12:17.602 --> 12:19.269
It should live on the page

12:19.271 --> 12:21.721
with no protection.

12:21.723 --> 12:24.974
I think we should start
on the first page...

12:26.861 --> 12:30.897
Was there anything
that you liked?

12:30.899 --> 12:33.683
I think Marilyn Monroe
is an interesting subject

12:33.685 --> 12:36.719
for a musical.

12:36.721 --> 12:38.187
Tom, I was ambushed.

12:38.189 --> 12:41.458
He wants to change everything.

12:41.460 --> 12:43.409
So you didn't have fun
with our potential collaborator?

12:43.411 --> 12:45.328
Russell Crowe
is more collaborative.

12:45.330 --> 12:47.714
North Korea
is more collaborative.

12:47.716 --> 12:49.866
I'm going to Eileen's right now
to tell her

12:49.868 --> 12:53.369
that there is no way that
we are working with that man.

12:53.371 --> 12:54.387
Okay.

12:54.389 --> 12:56.256
Go to Eileen.
Get rid of the parasite.

12:56.258 --> 12:59.309
In the meantime,
I may have an idea.

12:59.311 --> 13:00.677
[Laughs]

13:00.679 --> 13:02.846
You look like the crazy dude
from <i>A beautiful mind.</i>

13:02.848 --> 13:03.897
You could help.

13:03.899 --> 13:05.515
I am.
I'm taking a hit every time

13:05.517 --> 13:08.351
you throw your hands up
like that.

13:08.353 --> 13:10.186
You think this is funny?

13:10.188 --> 13:11.821
Our meeting with Derek
is tonight.

13:11.823 --> 13:13.423
Look, you're the one
that told Karen

13:13.425 --> 13:15.057
we'd have it all written out.

13:15.059 --> 13:16.359
There are gaps...

13:16.361 --> 13:17.777
Things we lost when we moved

13:17.779 --> 13:22.916
or stuff out of order.

13:22.918 --> 13:26.786
Move.

13:26.788 --> 13:27.921
What?
This scene shouldn't be here.

13:27.923 --> 13:29.622
We had it at the top.

13:29.624 --> 13:32.408
We cut this song,
this one too.

13:32.410 --> 13:35.244
What? We had a better version
of this entire sequence.

13:35.246 --> 13:37.079
We worked on it all night,
wasted, remember?

13:37.081 --> 13:38.348
Fourth of July.

13:38.350 --> 13:39.549
I thought it was
on my computer,

13:39.551 --> 13:42.585
but I can't find it
anywhere.

13:47.257 --> 13:49.926
It's in my old notebook...

13:49.928 --> 13:54.230
Which I left back at...
Forget it.

13:54.232 --> 13:57.150
I thought this was
important to you.

13:57.152 --> 13:58.785
We'll remember it.
I'm sure.

13:58.787 --> 14:00.603
Not exactly
how it was.

14:00.605 --> 14:02.906
You can't go
back there, Jimmy...

14:02.908 --> 14:05.942
- [Sighs]
- End of story.

14:09.780 --> 14:11.631
- Hello.
- Hey.

14:11.633 --> 14:14.000
I can't believe <i>Bombshell's</i>
back in rehearsal.

14:14.002 --> 14:15.501
So what are we
working on?

14:15.503 --> 14:17.120
<i>Moving the line.</i>

14:17.122 --> 14:19.005
Just so long
as we're done by dinner.

14:19.007 --> 14:20.390
Hmm?

14:20.392 --> 14:22.892
Kyle Bishop
and Jimmy Collins?

14:22.894 --> 14:24.227
We're meeting them
tonight?

14:24.229 --> 14:28.765
Oh, no. Yeah, we'll be done
in plenty of time.

14:28.767 --> 14:31.768
What is it?

14:31.770 --> 14:35.355
I was starting to think I was
never going to be Marilyn again.

14:35.357 --> 14:37.240
I wouldn't let that happen.

14:37.242 --> 14:40.994
[Cell phone rings]
Will you excuse me for a sec?

14:40.996 --> 14:43.212
Ronnie, hi.
Listen, Derek...

14:43.214 --> 14:45.415
It turns out one
of the producers of <i>The Wiz</i>

14:45.417 --> 14:47.233
is in town right now.

14:47.235 --> 14:50.403
He was open to your idea,
but he's leaving town tomorrow.

14:50.405 --> 14:52.206
Um, we're presenting a number
from <i>Bombshell</i>

14:52.207 --> 14:53.256
for the team tomorrow.

14:53.258 --> 14:54.707
Why don't you just
bring him along?

14:54.709 --> 14:56.843
It's a beautiful song.

14:56.845 --> 14:58.711
It might serve
the same purpose.

14:58.713 --> 15:00.380
- I'll get him there.
- Okay, good.

15:00.382 --> 15:03.600
4:00, yeah?

15:03.602 --> 15:04.951
All right, everyone,

15:04.953 --> 15:07.169
tomorrow just got
a lot more important.

15:07.171 --> 15:09.522
Dancers, Karen's going
to sing a song,

15:09.524 --> 15:10.607
you're going to listen,

15:10.609 --> 15:12.174
and then we're going
to get to work.

15:12.176 --> 15:14.560
Karen?

15:14.562 --> 15:17.847
[They just keep moving the line
playing]

15:17.849 --> 15:20.817
♪ The field was bright
with clover ♪

15:20.819 --> 15:23.870
♪ I saw the finish sign

15:23.872 --> 15:26.956
♪ I started as a rover

15:26.958 --> 15:29.709
♪ and then
victory was mine ♪

15:29.711 --> 15:33.079
♪ I thought
the race was over ♪

15:33.081 --> 15:37.550
♪ but they just keep
moving the line ♪

15:37.552 --> 15:38.885
[Knock at door]
Tom?

15:38.887 --> 15:41.721
[Door opens, closes]

15:41.723 --> 15:44.757
♪ They cheered
at my persistence ♪

15:44.759 --> 15:46.876
Look how good you are
in the workshop last winter.

15:46.878 --> 15:48.111
Why are you watching this?

15:48.113 --> 15:50.847
I wanted to be reminded
of our initial instincts

15:50.849 --> 15:53.066
before jumping
back into it.

15:53.068 --> 15:55.268
Want to watch with me?

15:55.270 --> 15:57.720
Did you find the cd?

15:57.722 --> 16:00.490
[Gasps]
Thank you.

16:00.492 --> 16:02.892
Apparently
this is out of print.

16:02.894 --> 16:05.695
I've only seen
the <i>dangerous liaisons</i> movie.

16:05.697 --> 16:08.564
This was based on the book.
And it's a lost gem.

16:08.566 --> 16:10.283
It's about time
somebody revived it.

16:10.285 --> 16:15.404
Well, I may have talked my way
into an audition for it.

16:15.406 --> 16:16.506
For cecile?

16:16.508 --> 16:19.075
Oh, my God.

16:19.077 --> 16:20.843
That is the best part
in the show.

16:20.845 --> 16:22.929
Madeline kahn got nominated
for featured for it.

16:22.931 --> 16:25.014
Yeah, but I don't know
who I think I'm kidding.

16:25.016 --> 16:27.550
They're auditioning
real names for it,

16:27.552 --> 16:30.720
like Jen damiano
and Jessie Mueller, and I'm...

16:30.722 --> 16:32.588
Perfect for the part.

16:32.590 --> 16:35.324
Ivy, this could be
your breakout.

16:35.326 --> 16:37.276
I don't know
what came over me.

16:37.278 --> 16:40.413
I just knew
I wanted it.

16:40.415 --> 16:43.483
I never thought somebody'd
give me the chance after...

16:43.485 --> 16:46.652
♪ Keep moving...

16:46.654 --> 16:48.821
Just bring
what you brought here,

16:48.823 --> 16:51.040
and you'll crush
this audition.

16:51.042 --> 16:55.211
I'm sure of it.

16:55.213 --> 16:57.046
[Vocalizing]

16:57.048 --> 17:00.633
[Applause]

17:00.635 --> 17:03.886
Why can't they just set
the deposition?

17:03.888 --> 17:07.339
My whole company's waiting
on this.

17:07.342 --> 17:10.843
I don't care if they want
to find Nick felder first.

17:10.845 --> 17:14.430
My team should not be penalized
for their incompetence.

17:14.432 --> 17:15.681
No, Eileen.
No way.

17:15.683 --> 17:18.101
I have put in way too much work
to let this happen.

17:18.103 --> 17:20.936
I'm going to have
to call you back, David.

17:20.939 --> 17:23.689
Julia, what is it?
What's so important?

17:23.691 --> 17:25.525
I'm juggling
chain saws here.

17:25.527 --> 17:27.777
Peter gilman wants
to create a whole new <i>Bombshell.</i>

17:27.779 --> 17:30.329
I don't even think he wants
to call it <i>Bombshell.</i>

17:30.331 --> 17:32.665
His notes
were completely insane.

17:32.667 --> 17:34.867
I think he was rather
on the Mark myself.

17:34.869 --> 17:36.586
You knew about them?

17:36.588 --> 17:39.155
Well, how do you think
I chose him?

17:39.157 --> 17:41.090
He pitched his take
to me in Boston.

17:41.092 --> 17:43.943
He said
he never saw the show.

17:43.945 --> 17:47.346
Oh, Julia,
he saw it four times.

17:47.348 --> 17:49.515
This was a setup?

17:49.517 --> 17:52.334
I thought if you came
to this idea on your own

17:52.336 --> 17:55.138
that, uh,
you'd be more comfortable.

17:55.140 --> 17:57.857
I won't be forced to destroy
my work like this.

17:57.859 --> 17:59.058
Then you don't have to.

17:59.060 --> 18:01.310
Thank you.

18:01.312 --> 18:05.665
Julia, no one has invested
more in this show than I have.

18:05.667 --> 18:07.416
And if you don't want
to do the work,

18:07.418 --> 18:10.069
I will find someone
who will.

18:17.377 --> 18:19.995
♪ But I prayed ♪

18:20.097 --> 18:23.098
♪ the path
of least resistance led ♪

18:23.300 --> 18:25.500
♪ to Hollywood and vine

18:25.510 --> 18:27.728
No, no.
That's not it.

18:27.735 --> 18:30.202
Remember, this number
is about Marilyn realizing

18:30.204 --> 18:31.737
that being taken seriously
as an actress

18:31.739 --> 18:34.073
is not the same thing
as becoming a star.

18:34.075 --> 18:35.541
I understand the song.
Thanks.

18:35.543 --> 18:37.660
You might get it up here,
but I'm not feeling it in here.

18:37.662 --> 18:39.328
And when you come
downstage here,

18:39.330 --> 18:40.913
there should be a little sigh
in the movement

18:40.915 --> 18:42.297
before you pick yourself
back up.

18:42.299 --> 18:45.117
All right, let's take it
from the top, please.

18:47.637 --> 18:48.971
Ivy.

18:48.973 --> 18:50.422
- Hey.
- Hey.

18:50.424 --> 18:52.141
When you said
you were here,

18:52.143 --> 18:54.059
I didn't realize
<i>Bombshell</i> was back up.

18:54.061 --> 18:55.260
Yeah, a little bit.

18:55.262 --> 18:56.962
It's not legally cleared yet,
but soon.

18:56.964 --> 18:58.147
What's up?

18:58.149 --> 18:59.648
I was just going to ask
for a small favor,

18:59.650 --> 19:01.100
but I can see...
No, no, no, no.

19:01.102 --> 19:02.901
No, I could do
with an audience right now.

19:02.903 --> 19:05.604
Can you just watch something
for me, please?

19:05.606 --> 19:06.655
Well, uh,
I don't think that's...

19:06.657 --> 19:08.941
Ivy has a great eye.

19:08.943 --> 19:10.909
She can tell us
where we're going wrong.

19:10.911 --> 19:15.247
Okay, five minutes...
We'll take it from the top.

19:15.249 --> 19:19.118
Karen, couple of things.

19:19.120 --> 19:20.369
The makers
don't like the harvest,

19:20.371 --> 19:21.837
they refuse to produce
a single bottle.

19:21.839 --> 19:23.989
It's one of the most highly
regarded wines in the world.

19:23.991 --> 19:25.674
Tobacco, graphite, plum...

19:25.676 --> 19:28.326
You son of a bitch.

19:29.662 --> 19:30.929
Contrary to the way
this looks,

19:30.931 --> 19:32.514
I am not sleeping
with this woman.

19:32.516 --> 19:36.201
How did you like my show
in Boston, huh, liar?

19:36.203 --> 19:38.937
All four times you came?

19:38.939 --> 19:42.141
Excuse me a minute.

19:42.143 --> 19:45.310
How did you find me here?
You have a chatty doorman.

19:45.312 --> 19:47.112
Hmm. And this meeting
could not wait till tomorrow?

19:47.114 --> 19:50.199
Uh, a meeting is something
two people agree to.

19:50.201 --> 19:52.017
We've never had a meeting.

19:52.019 --> 19:53.202
That was a trap.

19:53.204 --> 19:56.155
If I have no choice,
then I want specifics...

19:56.157 --> 19:59.992
Act by act, scene by scene,
line by line.

19:59.994 --> 20:02.478
First of all,
I did not lie about Boston.

20:02.480 --> 20:03.746
You did not ask.

20:03.748 --> 20:04.997
Now, you want specifics?

20:04.999 --> 20:06.331
Fine. Let's talk
about the scope of your show.

20:06.333 --> 20:08.834
- Let's. Educate me.
- All right.

20:08.836 --> 20:10.335
You chose to focus
on DiMaggio, right?

20:10.337 --> 20:12.421
The domestication of Monroe,
barefoot in the kitchen

20:12.423 --> 20:13.689
making spaghetti sauce
for her man.

20:13.691 --> 20:15.507
- It's a good center.
- For what?

20:15.509 --> 20:16.642
You really think
an audience

20:16.644 --> 20:18.310
wants to watch Marilyn
the housewife?

20:18.312 --> 20:20.262
This show is

20:20.264 --> 20:23.182
about the biggest movie star
in the world

20:23.184 --> 20:25.717
feeling like she still needs
the stability of home

20:25.719 --> 20:27.552
to become
a complete woman.

20:27.554 --> 20:29.688
It's her struggle
to find balance

20:29.690 --> 20:31.323
between career and family.

20:31.325 --> 20:33.692
Look, that conflict might be
your way into Marilyn's story.

20:33.694 --> 20:36.078
But it is not necessarily
the most sellable

20:36.080 --> 20:37.529
or even relevant
to a Broadway audience.

20:37.531 --> 20:38.664
[Laughs]

20:38.666 --> 20:41.750
It's relevant
to most women I know.

20:41.752 --> 20:45.704
And women buy the majority
of the tickets on Broadway.

20:45.706 --> 20:48.123
Or maybe you concentrated
on DiMaggio

20:48.125 --> 20:50.459
because you were in love
with the actor who played him...

20:50.461 --> 20:52.094
[Gasps]

20:52.096 --> 20:53.545
Which, actually,
I find surprising,

20:53.547 --> 20:55.931
because it damn sure didn't come
through in the text.

20:55.933 --> 20:57.800
Marilyn Monroe
was the greatest sex symbol

20:57.802 --> 20:59.635
in American history, okay?

20:59.637 --> 21:03.222
And the show had no sex,
no sweat...

21:03.224 --> 21:04.756
Just a few sly songs

21:04.758 --> 21:06.892
with lyrics that faded to black
before it got good.

21:06.894 --> 21:09.478
I mean, where was the...
The steam on the windows, Julia?

21:09.480 --> 21:10.480
Huh?

21:10.481 --> 21:12.231
The excruciatingly slow
striptease?

21:12.233 --> 21:14.449
The, um...

21:14.451 --> 21:15.784
The heat?

21:15.786 --> 21:18.570
I don't know. Maybe you just
never felt it yourself.

21:18.572 --> 21:20.789
You think
I don't know heat?

21:20.791 --> 21:22.074
Mmmm.

21:22.076 --> 21:25.577
I broke up a perfectly good
marriage for heat.

21:25.579 --> 21:28.297
I sacrificed everything
for it.

21:28.299 --> 21:32.167
I know heat
better than anyone.

21:32.169 --> 21:35.671
Then prove it.

21:35.673 --> 21:39.758
[Pen clatters]
Go to hell.

21:41.794 --> 21:45.264
[Sighs]

21:45.266 --> 21:47.432
[Whispers indistinctly]

21:47.434 --> 21:50.652
[Chuckles]

21:56.276 --> 21:59.278
[Robyn's <i>Dancing on my own</i>
playing]

21:59.280 --> 22:06.869
♪

22:06.871 --> 22:10.222
♪ somebody said
you got a new friend ♪

22:10.224 --> 22:15.594
♪

22:15.596 --> 22:20.349
♪ does she love you
better than I can? ♪

22:20.351 --> 22:23.268
♪

22:23.270 --> 22:28.473
♪ there's a big, black sky
over my town ♪

22:28.475 --> 22:32.477
♪

22:32.479 --> 22:34.146
♪ I know where you're at

22:34.148 --> 22:37.065
♪ I bet she's around

22:37.067 --> 22:41.320
♪

22:41.322 --> 22:45.240
♪ yeah, I know
it's stupid ♪

22:45.242 --> 22:49.878
♪ I just got to see it
for myself ♪

22:49.880 --> 22:52.047
♪ I'm in the corner

22:52.049 --> 22:54.132
♪ watching you kiss her

22:54.134 --> 22:57.336
♪ oh

22:57.338 --> 23:00.589
♪ I'm right over here

23:00.591 --> 23:02.641
♪ why can't you see me?

23:02.643 --> 23:06.812
♪ Oh

23:06.814 --> 23:08.981
♪ I'm giving it my all

23:08.983 --> 23:13.268
♪ but I'm not the girl
you're taking home ♪

23:13.270 --> 23:15.570
♪ ooh

23:15.572 --> 23:17.439
♪ I keep dancing

23:17.441 --> 23:20.692
♪ on my own

23:20.694 --> 23:24.029
♪

23:24.031 --> 23:29.785
♪ ooh

23:29.787 --> 23:32.754
♪

23:32.756 --> 23:37.342
♪ I just came
to say good-bye ♪

23:37.344 --> 23:41.346
♪

23:41.348 --> 23:44.349
[Piano music playing]

23:44.351 --> 23:46.101
♪

23:46.103 --> 23:48.971
No, no, no!

23:48.973 --> 23:50.472
You're still
outside it, Karen.

23:50.474 --> 23:51.890
I don't understand
what you want.

23:51.892 --> 23:53.058
I'm not sure you do either.

23:53.060 --> 23:56.311
Okay, let's take five.

23:56.313 --> 24:00.432
Hey.

24:00.434 --> 24:03.068
I thought you wanted a favor.
I changed my mind.

24:03.070 --> 24:04.602
What, the number
was that bad?

24:04.604 --> 24:07.789
- It's not the number.
- Ivy, Ivy...

24:07.791 --> 24:09.741
What can I do
to make this better?

24:09.743 --> 24:12.160
It's not you.
I shouldn't have come.

24:12.162 --> 24:15.030
I meant the number.

24:19.002 --> 24:22.087
You're doubting yourself.

24:22.089 --> 24:23.855
You don't do that,
remember?

24:23.857 --> 24:27.592
And neither should I.

24:27.594 --> 24:31.563
[Dog barking]

24:33.000 --> 24:39.074
Advertise your product or brand here
contact www.OpenSubtitles.org today

24:42.775 --> 24:45.861
[Distant sirens wailing]

24:54.203 --> 24:56.705
You got balls, Jimmy.
I'll give you that.

25:06.103 --> 25:07.871
Hey.

25:07.873 --> 25:09.072
You're late.

25:09.074 --> 25:12.575
But it's okay.
Everyone is.

25:12.577 --> 25:15.411
I really hope
this is good enough.

25:15.413 --> 25:18.998
Will this help?

25:21.135 --> 25:22.969
Your lip...
Jimmy, what did you do?

25:22.971 --> 25:24.838
I told you
not to go back there.

25:24.840 --> 25:28.324
It's your one shot,
right, pal?

25:28.326 --> 25:30.226
Our shot, Jimmy.

25:30.228 --> 25:33.396
[Cell phone vibrating]

25:33.398 --> 25:35.765
Karen, hey.

25:35.767 --> 25:38.151
Really?
That's, um...

25:38.153 --> 25:39.269
Karen, what's up?

25:39.271 --> 25:41.354
Hey, I'm rehearsing
with Derek,

25:41.356 --> 25:43.022
and we can't get away.

25:43.024 --> 25:44.440
I'm so sorry.

25:44.442 --> 25:46.659
Um, the good news is,
is he knows you were ready,

25:46.661 --> 25:48.745
and he's very excited.

25:48.747 --> 25:49.946
Karen!

25:49.948 --> 25:52.999
I'll call you tomorrow
to reschedule, okay?

25:53.001 --> 25:54.117
What'd she say?

25:54.119 --> 25:57.420
Nothing.
Let's bounce.

26:00.457 --> 26:01.958
Ah, there you are.

26:01.960 --> 26:03.626
I've been waiting
to talk to you about some, um...

26:03.628 --> 26:05.328
Get your butt
in the studio now, Tom.

26:05.330 --> 26:07.514
We're going to be working
all night.

26:07.516 --> 26:11.885
I said, "now"!

26:11.887 --> 26:16.272
Valmont, you have asked,
and I have answered.

26:16.274 --> 26:19.976
But we cannot go on
like this.

26:19.978 --> 26:21.861
I belong to danceny.

26:21.863 --> 26:22.979
[Yawns]

26:22.981 --> 26:26.449
You wear jealousy well,
but on him...

26:26.451 --> 26:27.967
Sorry, Ivy.
It's not you.

26:27.969 --> 26:30.403
I was up all night
working with Julia.

26:30.405 --> 26:31.871
I don't blame you
for yawning.

26:31.873 --> 26:33.740
I'm so boring.

26:33.742 --> 26:36.192
And my accent's horrible.

26:36.194 --> 26:38.527
God, I should just cancel
the whole audition.

26:38.529 --> 26:39.546
Hey.

26:39.548 --> 26:41.881
You asked me for help.
Let me help.

26:41.883 --> 26:44.467
We just haven't found her yet.
And by "we," I mean "you."

26:44.469 --> 26:47.703
[Chuckles]
So who is cecile?

26:47.705 --> 26:50.590
At the start,
she's innocent.

26:50.592 --> 26:52.675
Unbroken.

26:52.677 --> 26:54.543
Mmhmm.
Untouched.

26:54.545 --> 26:56.846
Floating through a life
that's, uh...

26:56.848 --> 26:58.147
Preordained.

26:58.149 --> 27:00.233
Secretly waiting
for something, anything,

27:00.235 --> 27:01.317
to pull her out of it.

27:01.319 --> 27:03.019
Sounds like
Karen Cartwright.

27:03.021 --> 27:04.571
- Be nice.
- Sorry.

27:04.573 --> 27:06.889
I'm cecile.

27:06.891 --> 27:10.726
I'm innocent
and nice and yearning.

27:10.728 --> 27:11.744
Continue.

27:11.746 --> 27:14.514
So she's easily corrupted.

27:14.516 --> 27:19.035
Over time, though, she learns
to manipulate the men in turn.

27:19.037 --> 27:21.204
Oh, my God.

27:21.206 --> 27:22.372
She's Marilyn.

27:22.374 --> 27:24.073
You know who else she is?

27:24.075 --> 27:25.425
You.

27:25.427 --> 27:29.262
You know what it's like
to learn how to fight back.

27:29.264 --> 27:33.549
So cecile tortures the men
who hurt her.

27:33.551 --> 27:36.019
Sounds like fun.
You bet your ass it does.

27:36.021 --> 27:38.271
See, look at your face.
You're already feeling it.

27:38.273 --> 27:40.974
This role is in you.
You can do this.

27:40.976 --> 27:44.978
- Tom, five minutes.
- Okay.

27:44.980 --> 27:46.863
I'm so proud of you.
You're going to do great today.

27:46.865 --> 27:50.483
- Thank you.
- Okay.

27:50.485 --> 27:52.819
[Indistinct chatter]

27:55.873 --> 27:57.407
What's going on?

27:57.409 --> 27:58.908
Who are you?

27:58.910 --> 28:00.293
This is our friend Matt.

28:00.295 --> 28:02.445
He's going to be doing us
a favor for the day.

28:02.447 --> 28:04.213
You do realize we're
doing <i>moving the line</i> today?

28:04.215 --> 28:06.382
Not anymore.
We have a new number for you.

28:06.384 --> 28:10.003
Matt will play J.F.K.
until Simon arrives.

28:10.005 --> 28:11.971
No, we're doing my number
as planned.

28:11.973 --> 28:13.589
[Door opens]

28:13.591 --> 28:15.808
Oh, God, who's this one...
R.F.K.?

28:15.810 --> 28:19.128
No, this is the dramaturg
you signed off on.

28:19.130 --> 28:20.346
You wanted him,

28:20.348 --> 28:22.098
now you're going to watch
what I've done.

28:22.100 --> 28:25.134
Okay, this is Kennedy
and Marilyn,

28:25.136 --> 28:27.437
the mating dance
between them

28:27.439 --> 28:30.106
at bing Crosby's country home

28:30.108 --> 28:33.910
that leads to the first time
they have sex.

28:38.482 --> 28:40.450
This isn't going to help you
with <i>The Wiz.</i>

28:40.452 --> 28:42.168
No, it's not.

28:42.170 --> 28:45.088
I texted Karen again,
but I haven't heard back yet.

28:45.090 --> 28:46.756
I'm sure she'll call later
with a new time.

28:46.758 --> 28:49.292
Oh, yes, much later...

28:49.294 --> 28:52.512
Like, eight months
or never.

28:52.514 --> 28:54.931
Karen's worked too hard
to just disappear.

28:54.933 --> 28:58.017
She got Derek excited about us
and recorded a demo for free.

28:58.019 --> 28:59.502
And you're...
You're basing this on what?

28:59.504 --> 29:00.953
You've known her
for two minutes.

29:00.955 --> 29:03.690
I can just tell.
She's not fake.

29:03.692 --> 29:06.059
Promise.

29:14.034 --> 29:16.185
Look, we haven't had much time
to work on this.

29:16.187 --> 29:17.954
All right,
let's see what you've got.

29:17.956 --> 29:19.372
All right, we'll just have
to stagger through

29:19.374 --> 29:20.374
from the start, okay?

29:20.375 --> 29:23.242
Okay.

29:23.244 --> 29:26.129
It's good of you
to come, Henry.

29:26.131 --> 29:27.880
Veronica believes
in you.

29:27.882 --> 29:30.249
I figure I owe her
the benefit of the doubt.

29:30.251 --> 29:32.085
You're very kind.

29:32.087 --> 29:33.419
Ronnie, come here.

29:33.421 --> 29:35.838
Listen, there's been a bit
of a change of plan.

29:35.840 --> 29:38.808
Um, we're going to do a number
that's not exactly PG, you know?

29:38.810 --> 29:40.476
So if you want to just go
for drinks,

29:40.478 --> 29:42.044
I can meet you after.

29:42.046 --> 29:44.180
Well, we're here.
We want to watch you work.

29:44.182 --> 29:45.765
It'll be fine.

29:45.767 --> 29:47.683
Okay.

29:47.685 --> 29:50.737
Don't say
I didn't warn you.

29:50.739 --> 29:52.772
Enjoy.

29:55.359 --> 29:56.392
Here we go.

29:59.826 --> 30:04.449
OK, so the scene is been caught
somewhere in Palm Springs.

30:04.451 --> 30:06.267
Kennedy and Marilyn
have arranged to meet

30:06.269 --> 30:07.619
for the first time.

30:07.621 --> 30:09.154
[Sultry music]

30:09.156 --> 30:10.288
The space is transformed.

30:10.290 --> 30:15.210
We hear music,
the sounds of a party.

30:15.212 --> 30:17.045
Kennedy sees Marilyn enter,

30:17.047 --> 30:20.081
and their eyes lock
across the room.

30:20.083 --> 30:24.919
♪

30:24.921 --> 30:28.122
- Mr. President.
- Oh, call me Jack.

30:28.124 --> 30:30.325
I'm a huge fan
of your pictures.

30:30.327 --> 30:32.727
I'm a fan of yours
as well.

30:32.729 --> 30:37.465
Glad to finally meet you
in the, uh, flesh.

30:37.467 --> 30:39.601
- Disappointed?
- [Scoffs]

30:39.603 --> 30:41.269
Shall we go somewhere
to talk,

30:41.271 --> 30:43.154
get to know
each other better?

30:43.156 --> 30:44.972
Somewhere where there's...

30:44.974 --> 30:48.809
♪ No FBI getting nervous

30:48.811 --> 30:52.864
♪ no CIA peeking through

30:52.866 --> 30:55.667
♪ I've got
my own secret service ♪

30:55.669 --> 30:59.621
♪ to take care of you

30:59.623 --> 31:02.957
We can get to know each other
right here, can't we?

31:02.959 --> 31:04.843
Why don't we go where...

31:04.845 --> 31:08.546
♪ No one from <i>Time</i>
or from <i>Newsweek</i> ♪

31:08.548 --> 31:12.467
♪ can document
our rendezvous? ♪

31:12.469 --> 31:15.303
♪ it's our little secret

31:15.305 --> 31:18.139
♪ just us two

31:18.141 --> 31:21.226
everyone's watching.

31:21.228 --> 31:23.177
Is your wife?

31:23.179 --> 31:25.346
Jackie doesn't approve
of my parties

31:25.348 --> 31:28.900
or my friends.

31:28.902 --> 31:31.786
I hear you have
a lot of friends.

31:31.788 --> 31:32.820
Maybe that's why.

31:32.822 --> 31:35.456
Our host wants
to see you.

31:35.458 --> 31:37.825
Bing?
Now?

31:37.827 --> 31:40.628
Where is he?

31:40.630 --> 31:43.581
I had to get you alone.

31:43.583 --> 31:45.300
Do you always get
what you want?

31:45.302 --> 31:47.752
I haven't told you
what I want yet.

31:47.754 --> 31:50.054
How about I never do...

31:50.056 --> 31:51.639
And you have
to guess?

31:51.641 --> 31:56.561
♪ Outside of this room,
there's a cold war ♪

31:56.563 --> 32:00.431
♪ but you'd never know it
in here ♪

32:00.433 --> 32:02.717
♪ there's just
no defense ♪

32:02.719 --> 32:04.719
♪ the heat's
too intense ♪

32:04.721 --> 32:09.524
♪ and, oh, how it rises
whenever you're near ♪

32:09.526 --> 32:11.776
You want the same thing
everyone wants.

32:11.778 --> 32:14.495
I thought
you'd be different.

32:16.448 --> 32:20.868
♪ So let's do it now
for our country ♪

32:20.870 --> 32:24.589
♪ raise the old
red, white, and blue ♪

32:24.591 --> 32:27.241
♪ it's our little secret

32:27.243 --> 32:31.179
♪ just us two

32:31.181 --> 32:35.433
♪ just us two

32:35.435 --> 32:39.938
♪ just us two

32:45.894 --> 32:49.597
[clapping]

32:54.036 --> 32:55.870
Who are you?

32:55.872 --> 32:57.956
You must be Derek.
I'm... I'm Jimmy Collins.

32:57.958 --> 33:01.609
Jimmy who?

33:01.611 --> 33:03.628
Exactly.

33:09.668 --> 33:13.338
That's supposed to change
our minds?

33:17.009 --> 33:19.344
[Exhales]

33:19.346 --> 33:21.896
That was absolutely
the right direction for Kennedy.

33:21.898 --> 33:24.399
It's got glamour,
power, sex.

33:24.401 --> 33:25.850
It's the new Broadway.

33:25.852 --> 33:27.435
Good job.

33:27.437 --> 33:29.570
Look at you.

33:29.572 --> 33:31.189
You proved me wrong.

33:31.191 --> 33:34.025
That was almost an apology.
Try again.

33:34.027 --> 33:35.576
Am I supposed to be sorry
for something?

33:35.578 --> 33:37.829
The way you talked
to me yesterday, for starters.

33:37.831 --> 33:40.531
I'm not sorry about that.
I rather enjoyed it myself.

33:40.533 --> 33:42.367
You're even crazier
than I thought.

33:42.369 --> 33:43.584
Oh.

33:43.586 --> 33:45.986
Now, tell Eileen
that I did this on my own

33:45.988 --> 33:47.755
and that we won't be needing
your services.

33:47.757 --> 33:49.257
On your own?

33:49.259 --> 33:51.759
You never would have written it
without me pushing you.

33:51.761 --> 33:54.846
Sorry, kid.
You're stuck with me now.

33:57.583 --> 34:00.468
Oh, my God, Tom.
Tom, guess what.

34:00.470 --> 34:02.887
I got the part.
I am cecile.

34:02.889 --> 34:06.391
Oh, my God.

34:06.393 --> 34:07.859
Ivy!
[Giggles]

34:07.861 --> 34:09.844
Yeah, they said
all the other girls

34:09.846 --> 34:11.112
played the innocence,

34:11.114 --> 34:13.179
and I found the drive
underneath.

34:13.181 --> 34:15.699
I wish you could see my face.
I'm grinning like an ape.

34:15.702 --> 34:17.068
After everything
that's happened,

34:17.070 --> 34:19.520
you're the one who's going
to be on Broadway.

34:19.522 --> 34:20.822
Well, thanks to you.

34:20.824 --> 34:22.739
You'd make a really great
director, you know.

34:22.742 --> 34:24.375
[Scoffs]
Please.

34:24.377 --> 34:25.960
[Laughs]
Seriously.

34:25.962 --> 34:28.246
You understand style
and intention,

34:28.248 --> 34:30.380
and you know how to get
the best out of people

34:30.382 --> 34:31.966
without torturing them.

34:31.967 --> 34:33.217
That's no small thing.

34:33.219 --> 34:36.054
Hmm.
Art without torture...

34:36.056 --> 34:37.922
I don't think
it's possible.

34:37.924 --> 34:39.005
What happened
to your lip?

34:39.007 --> 34:40.208
It doesn't matter,
all right?

34:40.208 --> 34:42.760
Jimmy, I'm sorry
about the last few days.

34:42.762 --> 34:43.978
It's just been crazy...

34:43.980 --> 34:45.396
You don't have
to explain, Karen.

34:45.398 --> 34:46.681
Your show is
in rehearsals.

34:46.683 --> 34:48.065
It's totally fine.
I get it.

34:48.068 --> 34:49.516
Just because I'm in <i>Bombshell</i>
doesn't mean

34:49.518 --> 34:51.819
I'm any less available
for you and Kyle.

34:51.821 --> 34:53.938
I totally meant what I said
about your musical.

34:53.940 --> 34:55.606
We're going to get it moving.
Uh, how?

34:55.608 --> 34:57.191
Derek doesn't even know
who the hell we are.

34:57.193 --> 34:58.242
That's not true.

34:58.244 --> 35:00.111
I played him your songs,
and he loved it.

35:00.113 --> 35:01.729
He was just
in the moment,

35:01.731 --> 35:04.332
and it was our first day
in rehearsal in a long time,

35:04.334 --> 35:05.917
and he just couldn't place you,
that's all.

35:05.919 --> 35:10.772
Look, I really don't care
either way.

35:10.774 --> 35:11.923
This is just
a bunch of crap

35:11.925 --> 35:13.341
that I scribbled down
when I was wasted.

35:13.343 --> 35:15.293
But to Kyle,
this is everything.

35:15.295 --> 35:16.928
And for the first time
in his life,

35:16.930 --> 35:18.262
you have him believing

35:18.264 --> 35:19.881
that the one thing
that he's ever wanted

35:19.883 --> 35:21.132
could actually come true.

35:21.134 --> 35:23.468
And if that's not the case,
you tell him.

35:28.873 --> 35:30.373
****

35:30.531 --> 35:33.022
- Then let's talk process going forward.
- What are you thinking?

35:33.048 --> 35:35.751
Well, now that you know
I can hit a scene out of the park,

35:35.753 --> 35:36.753
I think it would be good

35:36.754 --> 35:38.537
to go back
and take a broader view.

35:38.539 --> 35:39.539
I don't agree.

35:39.540 --> 35:41.123
About a broader view?

35:41.125 --> 35:42.874
No, that she hit the scene
out of the park.

35:42.876 --> 35:45.210
Excuse me?

35:45.212 --> 35:47.879
Everyone loved the scene.

35:47.881 --> 35:50.182
Well, that's
because it was good,

35:50.184 --> 35:51.350
but it wasn't right.

35:51.352 --> 35:53.518
- What the hell does that mean?
- Oh, come on.

35:53.520 --> 35:54.937
Julia, you got it backwards.

35:54.939 --> 35:57.973
You had Kennedy as the predator
and poor Marilyn as the prey.

35:57.975 --> 36:00.142
He and Bobby
destroyed Marilyn.

36:00.144 --> 36:02.477
[Laughs] You know,
for such a sophisticated woman,

36:02.479 --> 36:04.730
that's an incredibly naive
point of view.

36:04.732 --> 36:06.698
I mean, Marilyn only slept
with very powerful men

36:06.700 --> 36:09.768
who could help her,
ergo, she was the predator.

36:09.770 --> 36:11.069
"Ergo"?

36:11.071 --> 36:13.438
Jack and Bobby's cruelty
led to her death.

36:13.440 --> 36:15.540
But I guess
she was asking for it, huh?

36:15.542 --> 36:16.708
Blame the victim.

36:16.710 --> 36:19.628
Now, that is
a sophisticated point of view.

36:19.630 --> 36:21.413
Jack and Bobby died too.
Let's not forget it.

36:21.415 --> 36:22.547
Oh, are you saying

36:22.549 --> 36:24.633
Marilyn Monroe
killed the Kennedys?

36:24.635 --> 36:26.885
Did you run that little twist
by Eileen

36:26.887 --> 36:28.787
in Boston
on one of your four trips?

36:28.789 --> 36:30.789
Mm, it's a lot better than
shadow selves, that's for sure.

36:30.791 --> 36:33.008
- Now those are out?
- With extreme prejudice.

36:33.010 --> 36:34.059
Ding, ding, ding.

36:34.061 --> 36:35.761
Both of you,
back to your corners.

36:35.763 --> 36:38.263
Take a rest.

36:39.849 --> 36:42.100
Wow.

36:48.024 --> 36:49.691
You're still here?

36:49.693 --> 36:50.826
I came back.

36:50.828 --> 36:52.194
Sorry I ran out before.

36:52.196 --> 36:53.662
It's okay.

36:53.664 --> 36:57.916
Seeing what you did up there
made me jealous.

36:57.918 --> 37:00.202
I've never been allowed
chances like that.

37:00.204 --> 37:01.670
When I first got
in this business,

37:01.672 --> 37:03.205
all I wanted to do
was get to the top,

37:03.207 --> 37:04.623
but now I'm stuck here...

37:04.625 --> 37:05.625
Broadway's sweetheart

37:05.626 --> 37:07.876
playing Dorothy
at almost 30 years old.

37:07.878 --> 37:09.127
It's not too late.

37:09.129 --> 37:10.962
Which is why I just
dropped out of <i>The Wiz.</i>

37:10.964 --> 37:14.332
It's time I show everyone
what I'm capable of.

37:14.334 --> 37:15.600
What can I do to help?

37:15.602 --> 37:19.521
I want to do
a one-night-only show...

37:19.523 --> 37:21.673
The kind of concert
that people will talk about

37:21.675 --> 37:23.942
years from now,
kick themselves for missing.

37:23.944 --> 37:25.176
Of course.

37:25.178 --> 37:27.062
I want the world to know
that Veronica Moore

37:27.064 --> 37:29.614
is not their Broadway baby
anymore.

37:29.616 --> 37:30.982
Can you do that?

37:30.984 --> 37:32.868
Can you?

37:32.870 --> 37:34.569
[Sighs]

37:34.571 --> 37:36.705
It's scary,
but if I'm going to grow,

37:36.707 --> 37:38.073
I got to take this chance.

37:38.075 --> 37:40.992
You want to grab a drink
and talk about it?

37:40.994 --> 37:42.193
Uh, yeah.

37:42.195 --> 37:43.829
You know what?
Can we just take a rain check?

37:43.831 --> 37:45.530
There's something
I've got to do.

37:45.532 --> 37:47.416
But we'll do it
very soon, okay?

37:47.418 --> 37:49.051
Karen!

37:49.053 --> 37:50.886
[Knock at door]

37:50.888 --> 37:54.172
[Laughs]

37:54.174 --> 37:56.258
Uh, Jimmy,

37:56.260 --> 37:57.943
Karen's outside
with Derek Wills.

37:57.945 --> 38:01.263
You're that drunk already?

38:01.265 --> 38:03.065
You're such a lightweight.

38:03.067 --> 38:04.433
No, they are really here.

38:04.435 --> 38:05.717
Yeah, well, they can go

38:05.719 --> 38:08.386
'cause I am not having
this meeting right now.

38:08.388 --> 38:10.489
Screw them.

38:10.491 --> 38:11.907
What did I just s...

38:11.909 --> 38:13.492
Hi. Derek.

38:13.494 --> 38:15.994
Kyle bishop.

38:15.996 --> 38:20.082
I can't believe you're standing
in my apartment.

38:20.084 --> 38:23.502
Hello, again, Jimmy.

38:23.504 --> 38:25.470
I'm Derek.

38:25.472 --> 38:28.206
I like your work.

38:31.076 --> 38:33.712
Sorry.
I was a bit busy earlier.

38:33.714 --> 38:36.247
Plus, I'm not a huge fan

38:36.249 --> 38:38.366
of uninvited guests
in my rehearsal room.

38:38.368 --> 38:40.702
Well, you had a lot
on your plate.

38:40.704 --> 38:43.054
Yes, I did.

38:46.025 --> 38:48.610
But I'm here now.

38:55.985 --> 38:59.187
It's cool you came.
You kept your promise.

38:59.189 --> 39:01.873
That's, uh...
[Bottles clink]

39:01.875 --> 39:03.825
That's rare.
Beer?

39:03.827 --> 39:06.411
Thank you.

39:06.413 --> 39:08.463
So there's this kid,
right?

39:08.465 --> 39:10.332
He comes
from a nothing family.

39:10.334 --> 39:13.668
You know, dad dies,
mom remarries some animal,

39:13.670 --> 39:14.753
beats the crap
out of him.

39:14.755 --> 39:16.388
Uh, the kid packs up.

39:16.390 --> 39:17.806
He lives on the streets...

39:17.808 --> 39:20.342
Drugs, stealing,
you know, whatever.

39:20.344 --> 39:21.810
You've heard
all this stuff before,

39:21.812 --> 39:24.062
which is why it's all done away
with in the opening number.

39:24.064 --> 39:25.147
He hates the world.

39:25.149 --> 39:26.364
He thinks everybody's
against him,

39:26.366 --> 39:27.632
which...
He's probably right.

39:27.634 --> 39:30.101
He wishes he could show everyone
how they really are.

39:30.103 --> 39:33.021
And I should care
if he does because what?

39:33.023 --> 39:35.440
His music.
Right?

39:35.442 --> 39:37.809
It's, like,
the one thing he's got...

39:37.811 --> 39:41.329
Songs about all the people
who've lied to him,

39:41.331 --> 39:42.914
uh, people
who've broken his heart,

39:42.916 --> 39:44.416
tried to take him,
been fake.

39:44.418 --> 39:46.585
He calls them his "hit list."
It's how he gets his revenge.

39:46.587 --> 39:48.152
Yeah, they're good.

39:48.154 --> 39:50.255
I mean, they're maybe great,
but he's a nobody from nowhere,

39:50.257 --> 39:52.591
with no way out
and no way in.

39:52.593 --> 39:56.044
Until he meets this girl
that he can't have.

39:56.046 --> 39:57.546
Oh, there's always a girl.

39:57.548 --> 39:59.514
She's rich.
She's... she's beautiful.

39:59.516 --> 40:01.099
She has everything
money can buy,

40:01.101 --> 40:03.167
and she has
this amazing voice.

40:03.169 --> 40:05.303
You know, she wants to be
a singer, but, you know,

40:05.305 --> 40:07.772
who cares about what
some rich girl wants, you know?

40:07.774 --> 40:10.292
You know, she's never even
given him a second look

40:10.294 --> 40:14.062
till she hears him playing
one of his songs one night.

40:14.064 --> 40:15.179
[Playing piano chords]

40:15.181 --> 40:17.282
They hang out, hook up,
you know.

40:17.284 --> 40:20.101
Total dream come true
for this guy.

40:20.103 --> 40:23.538
But in the morning,
the girl's gone.

40:23.540 --> 40:26.024
Disappears...
Not even her family knows where.

40:26.026 --> 40:28.910
Until he hears his songs
on the radio...

40:28.912 --> 40:31.079
Sung by her.
Yeah, she stole them.

40:31.081 --> 40:34.216
She changed her name.
She became someone else.

40:34.218 --> 40:37.586
You know, and... and after
a while, she needs more,

40:37.588 --> 40:39.387
because she's like...
Like a junkie now,

40:39.389 --> 40:43.225
but her drug is fame.

40:43.227 --> 40:44.960
And he gives them to her.

40:44.962 --> 40:46.962
He gives them to her
because he loves her.

40:46.964 --> 40:49.648
He doesn't care
if she is using him.

40:49.650 --> 40:50.782
He doesn't care

40:50.784 --> 40:52.717
if his love for her
destroys him,

40:52.719 --> 40:56.571
because when he
hears her sing...

40:59.358 --> 41:02.160
Um, you know,
it gets pretty dark after that.

41:02.162 --> 41:04.913
There's all these
other characters too.

41:04.915 --> 41:06.498
So it's <i>a star is born</i>
<i>plus Hamlet</i>

41:06.500 --> 41:08.066
with a bit
of <i>Romeo and Juliet.</i>

41:08.068 --> 41:10.118
<i>Moulin Rouge,</i>
<i>Gaga, J.T. Leroy...</i>

41:10.120 --> 41:11.953
Or none of those things.
It...

41:11.955 --> 41:15.040
You like it.

41:15.042 --> 41:17.776
It feels quite current.

41:17.778 --> 41:20.378
I think <i>Hit list</i> might be
quite a good title, don't you?

41:20.380 --> 41:23.098
Uh, well,
I'm warning you...

41:23.100 --> 41:26.101
Just... everybody dies
in the end.

41:26.103 --> 41:27.469
No, they don't.

41:27.471 --> 41:29.971
You just need
one really good death,

41:29.973 --> 41:31.523
but we'll get to that.

41:31.525 --> 41:34.059
Good, 'cause we kind of
don't have the second act yet.

41:34.061 --> 41:37.545
Well, that's lucky.
Second acts are my speciality.

41:37.547 --> 41:39.864
God knows I've had enough
of them myself.

41:39.866 --> 41:41.199
Right, why don't we have
some more beers,

41:41.201 --> 41:43.618
and we can talk
about how this might work?

41:43.620 --> 41:45.120
Even better,
I'll get the beers

41:45.122 --> 41:46.871
while Jimmy
plays you some songs.

41:46.873 --> 41:48.907
[Laughs]
On it.

41:57.750 --> 42:02.637
[Indistinct chatter]

42:09.178 --> 42:11.730
Why don't we take it
from the top?

